text:
Pros: The ice maker is really efficient. And it gets more efficient after the first couple of batches. For my family purposes it is therefore more than enough. I did not find the ice to melt fast when kept in the bucket, but I have only used it inside my house during the fall so far.
Cons: I found it to be more noisy than what I expected from reading other reviews. It sounds like a fridge, though a small one. The other thing with which I was a little bit disappointed was the size of the ice. The small size is really small. The large one is acceptable though. A picture of a piece of ice that comes out when the large ice mode is selected is attached. And yes, it melts pretty fast, but I don't mind. It gets the drink cold, and I always put a lot of ice in my drinks anyway. I am accustomed to watery drinks. I am certain the other models available that use the same technology will have similar performance results.

In summary, I would say it is worth the price. Apart from the noise, the other reviews are pretty accurate.

text: The EZ-Scoop is used to load loose coffee grounds into the filter that is supplied for this purpose with my Keurig when I am not using pre-filled K-cups. The funnel part is folded back to scoop grounds into to the bottom portion and then swung on top to pour the grounds into the filter. It allows more controlled pouring of grounds into the filter than using a spoon or other type of scoop. Prevents spilling of grounds while filling the filter. I add a paper filter into the metal filter to make for quick cleanup of the filter after brewing. Paper filter and used grounds are easily thrown away and the metal filter is just rinsed with its holder between uses. The EZ-Scoop does not have to be cleaned until the end of the day. Advantage: If you like brewed coffee, this technique allows precise choice and good flavor from your Keurig. Not always the case with K-cups. Less expensive than K-cups. Disadvantage: Takes a bit more time than popping in a K-cup. But the flavor is worth it.

text:
This is not a "plug and play" water drain pump replacement part for a Kenmore Elite HE4T model number 110.45992.400. However, on the Amazon page it did show this to be the correct part based on this model number.

The specific problem is the wiring connection on the back of the pump (on the magnet). It does not match to the original part, therefore, you can't plug the wiring harness from your washer into the new part because the connections do not match. I was [however] able to make the part work, by putting the old magnet from the broken impeller on the new impeller that I purchased (giving me the right electrical connection). Then I had to cut the original plastic housing to make the pieces go back together properly. Ultimately once I did all this custom work and reinstalled the part on my washer the pump did work, and I can do laundry, but clearly this was not an easy plug and play swap to get my washer working again.

This part seems much louder than the original. I've decided if this part doesn't last, next time I'll spend the extra money and buy the entire housing. I would not recommend this part as a fix if you have the same Kenmore model that I listed. I can't speak for other models, but it is definitely not a "plug and play" for this model.

text:
My front-loading Kenmore washer started making very loud noises, disturbing my downstairs neighbors, so I bought this portable washer to help me survive until I can get my regular washer fixed. I wish I had bought it months earlier. I love this thing.

The adapter that came with it fit my kitchen faucet perfectly, so I was able to start using it within fifteen minutes of bringing it inside the house.

It is small. At most I can fit two pairs of jeans OR two bath towels (plus a t-shirt and socks, etc. for balance). As a single guy, that's all I need. In fact, I have a new-found love of doing small loads of laundry, since the smaller jobs are much less daunting.

It takes up space in front of just one basin of my dual-basin kitchen sink, and I've hooked the drain hose to my dish rack to keep the hose from flopping around during the drain cycle. If I have guests coming over, I can easily wheel the washer into the utility closet.

The only thing I don't like is how top-loading washers tend to get your clothes twisted and tangled together. I've been spoiled by my front-loader for so long that I had forgotten that top-loaders do this. A minor quibble, no fault of this washer itself.

text:
We needed to replace our almost worn out iCoffee iCups, which have been the most reliable, easy to clean and positive sealing lid reusable pods we have tried in the last 7 years. Unfortunately they are no longer available.

After research and checking reviews we chose to try these pods, especially since they were closest in design and without the needle basket in the lid, which I prefer.

Received the pods and scoop, the scoop which does work well once you develop your technique for it, and washed them first. They do appear more cheaply made than the iCups and also use a molded one piece design, the lid being attached to the basket by a thinner section functioning as the hinge. This cheaper design usually doesn't hold up to regular use for very long before the hinge will break, but that remains to be seen. Better quality pods like the iCups have an actual separate hinge that allow the lid to be removed for easier cleaning or replaced.

All of that aside, of which I would have been willing to deal with, the deal breaker being the oversize of needle hole in the lid. The first use of the pod I put my regular amount of grounds in, which is about 1/4" below the top. I like strong coffee but have found that tamping the grounds down to get more coffee in actually makes for a weaker cup as the water is not able to saturate the grounds as easily or as evenly. I have since found on other coffee sites that this is a known issue in the use of reusable pods. Also, if you overfill, as the grounds absorb water, they swell, which often results in a mess, coffee grounds being forced out of the lid edges or needle hole in the lid.

That being said, at the first use, when opening the coffee maker lid I noticed a mess of water and grounds all over the top of the pod and underside of the maker lid. I thought I had overfilled the pod, but was sure I used the same amount I have regularly used with the iCups and other pods. So I actually lessened the normal amount another 1/8" and tried again. Same results.

After further examination I realized the problem. The needle hole in the pod lid was noticeably larger in diameter than my other pods, which allowed the water and grounds to spray out around the needle when the water was being sprayed into the pod. It took filling the pod to only half capacity to stop this mess from being made, totally unacceptable. We are throwing them away.

Someone else's experiences might be different but that was mine and therefore I cannot recommend this product.

Very nice for a bachelor who only washes a small load most weeks. Even so, the wash load must be broken into at least 2 loads to spin "dry" (a damp dry, but a day on a rack finishes the job). The washer takes only 10-15 minutes to do it's work. I put the clothes into the spin dryer, pour a 5 gallon bucket of fresh water over them to rinse and then spin for 3-4 minutes. I usually finish 1-2 wash loads (and 4-5 "dryer" loads) in about an hour (except on sheets day once a month which adds 30 more minutes.) This little unit does the job just fine! I've been using it for 9 weeks and it's proven so far. Cheaper & easier than going to the laundromat!
Update September/2017: I note the dryer will not spin up if it is slow draining the rinse water. You might have to manhandle it to tip out the water. It is also temperamental about a balanced load. It can only do one pair of jeans at a time. But it remains a tough, dependable little workhorse after 3 months.
Update January/2020: Dryer has stopped working. I used it every other week for one load wash and 2-3 dryer loads. That gives it a life of about 2.5 years. I'm not too disappointed as this is to be expected I guess as it is more for RVs and temporary use then my regular use. Back to the laundromat until I can afford a new full size W/D.

text: This is my first wine cooler so I have no basis for comparison. If you buy this unit, ignore the temperature settings and buy a good digital thermometer. I had to set my cooler at 45 degrees to achieve a temperature range in the low to mid 50's. There is a difference in temperature of about 4 degrees between the top shelf and the lower shelf. As Fall approaches and the ambient temperature is cooling, the readings are getting lower. This morning my lower shelf read 49 degrees.  My house only got down to about 64 degrees last night. Be sure you are placing the cooler somewhere with lots of ventilation. At first I placed it in a large walk in closet allowing plenty of space around it on all sides. The unit ran constantly, heated the closet, and never achieved a temp below the high 50s. Moving it into my office solved that problem but that was a disappointment because I wanted my wine out of sight. I have some nice Syrah that I wanted to keep cool. Those bottles would not fit on the regular shelves. By removing the bottom rack I was able to shove in 3 bottles. I could also get those bottles into the two outside spaces on the top shelf. I have had to work with it and make adjustments but it seems to be functioning reasonably well now. I may be unrealistic but for $300. I had hoped for better than reasonably well. I have had the unit for one month so I can't comment on how it will do over the long run.

text: Maybe I got a bad one, but this thing leaks like a sieve.  I installed it on an existing roof, and I've installed similar vents before.  The roof pitch is 6 in 12, so fairly steep.  After installing I waited a day and then soaked the area using a hose.  Water poured into the inside of the duct.  This means that the flashing was good and I had properly flashed it to keep water from getting under the flange and around the duct hole.  The problem is that the uphill seam on this are not soldered or sealed in any way.  Water seeped in through the bottom seam along the uphill side, into a small gutter around the 6 inch vent, and then down the vent hole.  I could not believe how poorly it was designed/manufactured.  I didn't want to remove roofing and pull the nails, so I sealed the uphill seam with silicon and put a piece of aluminum flashing along the seam to protect the silicon.  DO NOT BUY THIS.  It isn't worth the hassle.  There are plenty of other vents on the market that have sealed seams.

text:
[[VIDEOID:d2d53ff7b9468ca5990500550dc3b74e]] I got this countertop ice maker because I was tired of never having ice in the house when I wanted it. It seemed like it would be the perfect solution to the problem I had and I was excited to get it set up and start using it.

The ice maker comes with an ice basket, an ice scoop, and bags to put the ice inside of. One of the biggest things I'd overlooked was the fact that this will not store and hold the ice. If you leave the ice in the basket it just melts into the water again. I hadn't realized that prior to ordering it, though it does say so in the product description.

The unit itself is really good quality and doesn't take up any more space than other countertop appliances. It's about the same size as our air fryer. The unit is easy to use and understand. There's a max fill line inside and a control panel on the top. The lid is in front of the panel where the water goes and the basket is inserted.

It takes quite a while for the unit to cool down and start producing ice. The ice builds up on the metal rods in the back of the machine. Once they're the correct thickness they drop into the machine and a plastic arm lifts them over the center and into the basket. Even after the unit had been running for a long time it still took longer than the 6-13 minutes for the ice to dump into the basket.

This system is far from efficient. I had to keep getting up and taking the ice out and adding it to the bag. After a couple of hours, I didn't even have half a bag of ice. I realize this is more convenient for some than going out and buying a bag of ice or waiting for a tray in the freezer to be ready, but it just takes so long and doesn't produce enough ice to be worth my time. For the energy I'm using to make the ice, I could have bought a 5 lb bag and called it good.

I can see this being handy if you don't have a freezer or you're trying to use it for an event, but I'm having a really hard time understanding how this is better or easier than either buying ice or making it with a tray in the freezer. Maybe I was too hopeful about what this product would do but it just takes too long and is too much of a hassle for me to continue using.

text:
I'm not installing this hood soon, but I have installed similar range hoods from Broan, so I can only assume that this one will be installed in a similar matter. It takes effort and is easier with a helping hand, but I'm one of those stubborn guys who usually insists upon doing everything myself.

It is always best to vent a range hood outside whenever possible since it expels ALL the grease and moisture-laden air out of the home, so that's how I will install this one eventually.

Several other reviewers suggest that the fan is noisy on high. No surprise there. When you move lots of air in a duct, especially a metal duct that does not have any sound deadening material, it gets noisy. But usually low or medium speed is all I need, and I can deal with a bit of extra noise if I have to run it on high occasionally.

In my opinion the price of this unit seems low for a range hood that looks this nice. I hope it works as well as I think it will. I gave it 4 stars because I cannot rate its actual installation requirements or longevity yet.

text:
[[VIDEOID:4d2ac93d0ad9d4cd99f4af1cdde72958]] I'm putting together a quick-and-dirty rec room in our basement so the kids have someplace to watch TV and play video games. I was given a couple of kitchen cabinets and small section of countertop, so I put a little "kitchenette" in the corner with a mini fridge and microwave. But, it's "dry" - there's no sink or running water, and the mini fridge keeps drinks more in the "slightly cool" range, as opposed to actually "cold". So I decided to try one of these countertop ice makers to provide ice in the event that some guests come over.

I like the compact size and the fact it doesn't seem to use much power. I plugged it in and added water (after waiting a day, per the instructions), hit the button, and... nothing. The "add water" light came on - but I had filled it up pretty close to the "max" line? OK, I added another half a bottle of water. It started pumping the water up and 10 minutes or so later I had ice!

It's kinda handy, but not without it's problems: It's LOUD. Louder than I expecting something this size could be, especially when it's pumping the water at the start of the cycle. And even when it's just running, the fan is powerful enough that I can sense the vibration from a few feet away. The machine doesn't actually refrigerate the ice holding area, so if you don't use the ice at a pretty good clip, it melts. There's always a bit of water left in the holding area, so I have to carry the whole unit upstairs to drain and dry it after an evening of using it. It needs to be refilled often - You'd quickly fall behind if you had more than 3 or 4 people using this throughout the course of an evening.

Overall it's a better option than nothing, or if you entertain a lot it's better than buying a bag of ice every time you host guests. And it would probably be a lot more handy if you're planning on keeping it on your kitchen counter right next to your sink, so you could fill or drain it at will. I'm glad to have it as a backup for occasional gatherings, camping trips, power outages, etc., but I don't know if I'd consider it a "use it day in and day out" kind of item.

text:
Broke in less that 6 months, but was nice while it lasted.
_____

UPDATE: After the six months, I realized that by changing the setting from large to medium, it would still make ice. It lasted another three months and then died. NewAir was great about replacing it. I sent in the old one, and had a brand-new one a few days later.

To be fair, we ran the unit 24x7 the whole time we had it, and we go through 20+ pounds of ice a day. I'm expecting the replacement unit to last about a year under the same conditions. So if you do the math, this really is a bargain. If I get 18 months of service from the two units, I would have purchased 540 bags of ice at roughly $3/bag, for a total of $1620. Instead, I get the same amount of ice for $180 (plus the cost of RO water & electricity) and no need to lug ice home from the store!

With regard to cleaning: This unit needs to be sanitized every couple of months. I found that white vinegar in a spray bottle works great. Spray the inside, let it sit, and then rinse it out. I then refill the unit with about a cup of vinegar and run it through a tank of water. One more clean tank of water, the vinegar taste is gone, and the machine is sanitized.

____

Update 7/3/17 - My replacement unit died today. Functioned as expected, lasting a little less than a year. It's clear that the manufacturer sells this exact unit to multiple brands with custom badging. I'm going to buy this same unit from one of the other brands here on Amazon and keep the NewAir around for spare parts... If you go this route and use the machine daily, expect to get 9-12 months out of it, and buy the 4 year replacement plan!

text:
WARNING: Be aware that not ALL Keurig and K-compatible machines can use these? They are the larger 'carafe' size, i.e. they only fit inside machines that support it.

And I mean 'freedom of choice', of course. This reusable K-cups set, provided by vendor as a 'for review' item, makes me a lot happier about keeping a Keurig machine on our kitchen counter because I was seriously thinking of demoting it to the garage.

After more than 2 months of happy daily use more than once daily of [[ASIN:B00W8MO0UO Fill N Save 3 Pack Reusable K-Cups for Keurig 2.0 & Backward Compatible With Original Keurig 1.0 Models]], I would say that they did pass the test of durability because they are as good today as they were more than 2 months ago. I can't state for a fact these reusable K-cups are as durable because I've only tried them for a couple of days now but, them coming from the same vendor and being of a more or less similar design, the odds are that they are as good as that other model and therefore are likely to save you lots of money in the long run.

Yes, the Keurig's idea is interesting because you can have coffee or tea very much instantly and you don't need to worry much about cleaning up before or after, other than throwing away the used cup. My issues with the method is that I must rely on someone else making a specific flavor available and if nobody does it the way I want it then... tough luck and, of course, the price. I was using the Keurig machine mostly for tea and the prices of those tea pods was bordering 'outrageous'.

But... enter the 'reusable' rebel movement. Yeah, I know, orange but who's looking? The cups are truly reusable. Yes, I do have to clean them even though for tea, it's actually not a bad idea to sometime add fresh tea leaves on top of the recently used old ones but I digress. So some cleaning is required. On the other hand, I can have my tea or my coffee exactly the way I want them and that's priceless.

As far as 'quality', see second paragraph. I know that they are not going to last forever because they are 'plastic' and there is a sealing rubber ring around the top but I suspect that they are going to last long enough to save me some serious money and always save me the frustration of not having my brew the way I want it.

text:
I bought the 7.7 lb version to wash cloth face masks more frequently than I can in the full size clothes washer. I'm surprised how much it can hold, easily 50-100 face masks. Most of the time I wash 10 at most, which this can handle without breaking a sweat.

The instructions are sparse and not very clear. I first put the laundry in the spin basket and put it on wash cycle. Predictably it failed by throwing the basket off the agitator. My mistake. The wash cycle spins both ways, but the basket is designed to hold only in one spin direction. Put the clothes directly in the basin without the spin basket. It stirs up the clothes as well as a full size washer.

It's a manual process of draining the basin after the wash cycle, refilling for rinse, then drain again after. The included fill hose doesn't fit my standard faucet, so I have to find an adapter of some sort. I manually fill using a mini bucket.

The spin cycle requires the spin basket (duh!). It's challenging to arrange the clothes so it's well balanced. Usually it wobbles like crazy and makes the unit shift around. With some experimentation I've figured out how to balance the load relatively well. The spinner does a good job drying the clothes. Not as good as the full size washer which spins much faster, but it's good enough. It wrings out as much water as hand wringing, with the benefit of not leaving wrinkles and stressing the fabric.

Overall this is a great product for small loads. Set your expectations accordingly. It requires more manual intervention than a full size clothes washer. It sure beats hand washing masks though. It's also 1/10 the price, can fit on a countertop, and is easily stored away.

Update: on the 3rd use, I thought it stopped working. The timer would tick but motor wouldn't engage. Turns out it has an over temp protection circuit. If it runs too long and gets hot inside, the over temp protection kicks in and you have to wait til it cools down. Inconvenient, but better than the unit destroying itself from overheating.

Itâ€™s amazing how far a large front-load washer can travel on a hard tiled floor, and I figured if I didnâ€™t find a solution soon I might come home one day to find my washing machine in my living room.

Most mats designed for this purpose had mediocre reviews, but then I stumbled on these little â€œhockey pucksâ€ and took a chance on them since their reviews were fairly positive. They have been nothing short of amazing. I put one of these discs beneath each foot of the two machines, and since then the washer and dryer have remained firmly planted to the floor. In 15 months they have not budged even an inch.

If you look at my photo, you can see that these discs are quite substantial, and they seem to be made of a very heavy and dense rubber. They arenâ€™t adhesive or particularly tacky, but they do seem to provide enough traction with the floor (probably helped by the weight of the machines) to keep the washer and dryer from moving.

Hereâ€™s a big tip: While these discs do a nice job of preventing my machines from relocating themselves, they do NOT address the â€œshakingâ€ problem. Even with these discs in place, if I washed a heavy load the machines would still rock back and forth -- this is probably made worse because they are both elevated few feet off the ground. To cut down on the shaking I used sheets of Dynamat, which are basically heavy adhesive sheets. I stuck three sheets to each side of my washer and two to each side of my dryer and they really cut down on the shaking. Amazon sells those as well: [[ASIN:B00YT7HXZK PLAIN PAK Dynamat Xtreme (8) Sheets 18"x32" 32 FTÂ² Bulk Consumer Grade Sound Damping]]

text:
Only had this ice machine for a week, but love it so far. Lacks a couple of key features that would REALLY make this a stand out product. The ice maker has an app, but other than to use it for turning the ice maker off or turning off the little night light that is built in, the app is not much use. Would be REALLY GOOD if the App would notify you when the machine has shut down so ice won't sit there and melt if you happen not to get back to it to check for a while.

When you fill it up and first turn it on, it runs for about 15 minutes before it starts making ice. Then it drops out really slowly for the first 45 to 60 minutes. Filling up the reservoir, (about 7 cups of water) takes about 3 hours to 3:15 to fill up the ice bin and shut off. Now that I've run through several cycles, I know to set the alarm on my phone to go back and check it after 3 hours.

Makes great ice... just like many restaurants serve. Also bought some ice bags to store it in... so we're not having to make ice 24 hours a day. Make a batch or so at a time and bag it, then pour it into the plastic freezer bin (purchased separately) as you use it. Great ice in drinks. Highly recommended so far. If anything changes, I'll come back and update my review.

text: My LG washing machine (from 2007 or 2008) began making unhappy noises that were getting worse.  A little research indicated that it was almost certainly one or more of the drum rollers.  (One of the front ones, it turned out, clearly had a bearing that was failing pretty badly).  I decided to give this kit a try because it was much cheaper than buying the OEM replacements from a specialty appliance site, as this kit includes all four rollers as well as the belt, idler pulley, and spring.  I replaced all four rollers and the belt, but didn't touch the idler pulley or spring.  The rollers seem to be very well-made and were identical to the OEM parts.  The only oddity is that you need two (2) washers and a nut for each roller, and this kit only includes one, so you'll need to use one of the original ones.  I ended up re-using all of the original washers and nut, simply because they seemed larger and maybe a tiny bit thicker than the ones that came with this kit.  That's the only reason I only gave 4 stars for the rating.  The repair was pretty easy (most of my time was spent removing dust and lint), and the reassembled washer is now as quiet as the day we first bought it.  I can't vouch for the longevity, (again, the rollers seem well-made and solidly constructed) but I'm very happy with this kit so far.

text:
Watch the video review for this product. It's really quite helpful and will give you ideas on how you can get a system going that works for you. If you buy this, get a system you can live with. As much as I encourage looking at someone else's review, here's my 2 cents.

Key points:
*The hoses are short, particularly the drain hose. Where you use this has to be within several feet of an outlet, a couple feet of a water source and pretty much right next to where you want to drain it. You can get around the hose length by using a bucket to add water (fill the bucket in a sink or tub and pour water in - the machine is indifferent to how the water is added, since that's a manual process anyway - the hose is a suggestion, not a requirement) or drain into a bucket or tub. Using buckets involves lifting a couple gallons of water a few times during the process, so sinks and drains are far more convenient. If you have the included hose too taut, it's more likely to pull off of the faucet, and that means water all over the place. I end up putting it in front of my bathroom sink and drain it into the toilet, as the tub is just too far away from the sink to make it convenient otherwise.
*You need to put it on something. It uses gravity to drain and the drain hose is at the bottom. I use a side table purchased for $12. It's rated for 30 pounds, which technically this is going to exceed when in use, but the weight is evenly distributed and shouldn't cause even a cheap little table to collapse. Elevating this by too much might make it harder to use for shorter folks (might be hard to reach in to get things if it's on an actual counter), but leaving it really low could cause some back strain. Find a cost effective and comfortable height that fits YOU, and remember that you'll have to interact with it a few times per load.
*You may find it stretches some of your clothes out or causes some items to pill. Use laundry delicates bags. They sell them in various sizes, and you want to use one big enough to let the garment move around, or put a few articles in the same bag. If you use a spin dryer, you can put them in the dryer still in the bags or take them out.
*There's no magic rinse cycle or spin cycle like on full sized washing machines. You drain and refill or rinse separately (you can do a few loads of wash in the same water if you'd like to - I don't pay for water where I live and we're not in anything close to a drought, so I'm okay with using a little bit more detergent to use fresh water every time). I typically run with detergent for the full 15 minutes, drain completely, refill completely to rinse (I may let it sit in the rinse water for a few minutes or even run the machine for 5 minutes or so if I think the clothes are more likely to retain detergent), drain again, and then have a second rinse with fabric softener if I choose to use it, during which I run the machine for 3-5 minutes to make sure it's distributed evenly. After the final drain, I wring each item out and then finish off in a spin dryer then hang to dry for a few hours. I keep a cheap colander with the laundry stuff to use to hold items between rinsing and putting them in the spin dryer, and have also used it for rinsing items that I pulled out before I put the fabric softener in. It lets things drip dry a little bit, which helps prevent unbalanced loads in the spin dryer.
*Capacity is several small items, or one larger item with really small items. I've washed full sized sheets (flat in one load, fitted in another). Adult pants can be washed with other things, depending on size (I'm a ladies 12 and I can get some shirts in the same load). A bath towel is a large item. Socks and other things like that can always go in with a large item. You can fill as much as can move decently well in the water, with the water level about 2/3 up. If you fill it more, it might splash out the drain hose.

Laundry is more involved than tossing in the washer and then in the dryer, but it's more convenient for those of us who can't have full sized machines. It's not too loud, but it's not silent. The timer ticks, the motor isn't super loud, but you can certainly hear it, and the water sloshes around when it spins. It's probably comparable to the dishwasher in my apartment, maybe slightly less noisy (my dishwasher is loud, though). This may be TMI, but I use reusable menstrual pads and it got one of those completely clean (after a pre-rinse under running water), so it certainly cleans sufficiently. I'm not running to the bank to get several rolls of quarters and can do laundry when I feel like it, not when my neighbors don't feel like doing their laundry (or just leaving their laundry in the machines...).

text:
I have had a Jiffy hat steamer for years. They have ruled the premium/professional hat steamer market since their inception. It was an easy choice to stick with Jiffy.
The instructions were simple: keep it always upright, don't run dry, empty after use.
My hat steamer requires distilled water, so I used distilled water in the E steamer.
Western shirts with permanent creases since purchased and an iron can't remove them? The Jiffy product made them disappear!
Two Filson wool jackets with hideous closet creases in back? Vanished in a couple of minutes!
I despise ironing. I own an iron, but rarely use it. This fine Jiffy product may end all ironing for me.
The pictures make the E steamer appear made out of bakelite with a 1930s style. It is not bakelite, just black plastic, though it feels durable. The style is vintage, perhaps Bauhaus. I appreciate the parts list, which tends to indicate a product built for the long haul, rather than disposable, like all the sleek competitors made in China.
I recommend using distilled water in anything that produces steam.
I read some reviews. The negative reviews are mostly operator error, or people that refuse to follow simple instructions. Use distilled water. Unplug and empty tank. It will be squeeky clean the next time you need it. If you like old school simplicity and durability, and American made, this is your model.

text:
Did quite a bit of research on these type of ice makers prior to buying this one, and thought this was my best option other than the 4k industrial nugget ice maker.
Pros:
Once you set it up it is easy to run. Add water when the low water light comes on, push dispenser for ice.
Ice is exactly what I wanted. Just like getting ice at Sonic.
Cons:
The amount of ice it says it produces on Amazon does not match directions in the box and is less than what it actually produces. It is much less.
You HAVE to use purified water. Tap water as well as filtered water wont work. It constantly puts itself in clean mode and you never get ice.
It is not as user friendly as it could be. You can't open it to see if there is ice. It gets dusty inside even though covered, and is difficult to clean. Adding water could be easier.
It is a little noisy while it is making ice.
Conclusion:
It does produce the ice I like, but not nearly enough. It is very heat sensitive. I had to move it 3 times before I found a spot it would actually produce ice. I seem to have found the right spot and I now get several glasses of nugget ice per day.

text:
I have high expectations for a washer because I use cloth diapers on my children. I was extremely happy with my previous traditional Kenmore Elite which did a fabulous job of getting diapers and clothes clean. When the agitator quit working the repair job was going to be a few hundred dollars less than new, so we thought we'd go with new. I wish I had spent the money on the repair.

I did lots of research and felt the GE was the best of old school and new. I wanted a top loader to be able to soak, but I did not want a locking lid. I wanted an agitator and I also wanted to be able to control the water level and the temperature. Despite the HE components like auto sense load and auto temp, this machine still lets you choose the water level so I thought I made the best choice. I also thought it was a great price compared to the new fancy machines with all the bells and whistles that I don't need in order to do a simple task like laundry.

When it was installed and I washed my first load, I was pleasantly surprised at how quiet it was. After a few loads however, it started making a bad squeaking sound that I knew was not normal. The big blue home improvment store that we bought it from was excellent about coming to replace it quickly. I could have chosen another machine, but I still felt this one had all the features that I wanted so I just got another one.

After a few more loads I had to figure out how to make the machine do what I really wanted it to do. Because of new government restrictions, hot is barely tepid. To get the machine to fill with all hot water from the water heater without getting diluted by cold water, I have to leave the lid up. The downside to this is if I forget to put the lid down, the load never starts. I've gotten use to it, but everyone once in awhile I forget long enough that the water cools down and I have to start all over. It's ridiculous to me. Hot should mean hot. I HAVE to wash diapers on hot and their version of hot is completely unacceptable.

To get the water level I want, I have to set the dial one to two loads above what I think it is. Large is really more like medium so if I fill the tub up with clothes, I have to select super to get as much water as I want. Don't change the dial while it's filling up because then the tub empties all the water and starts all over. Sort of defeats the water saving feature if you ask me.

So all of this was inconvenient and maybe annoying, but if it was cleaning clothes then I figured I could live with it. Wrong again. I was use to basic food or playground stains coming out with a little pre-treatment or something. Not with this machine. I have to put something through at least twice and I'm still not sure that the stain will come out. I've also had items like gym clothes that come out still smelling like sweat or a mixture of detergent and sweat. Yeah, gross.

It also cannot handle delicates. With my previous machine I could put in items that said hand wash and they would came out clean and in good shape. This machine leaves holes at the seam line in clothes that say to wash on gentle despite chosing the delicate cycle. I've also noticed that many of my kitchen towels and bath towels are starting to shred at the ends. Granted I've had some of these towels for years but I find it odd they ALL starting fraying after we got this machine.

The final straw with this machine is that it does not rinse well. My kids are not overly sensitive to detergents, but I've noticed that they have been scratching or are otherwise irriated after we've had this machine. I've noticed a difference for myself too. The biggest tell-tell sign is with diapers. It is very important that diapers are rinsed well so that leftover detergent doesn't irritate baby's skin potentially leading to a rash. Even when using the second rinse feature, or the fabric softener option, diapers are NEVER rinsed well. I can smell the detergent when I pull them out. And yes, I am using HE detergent. I've tried powders and liquids and the results are the same. I can run a load of diapers without new detergent and suds will float to the top of the water. To get my diapers as clean as they should be I have to run at least 3 hot loads while manually scooping out the suds. Consequently, I have grown to loathe this machine.

Now that we are expecting a third child I MUST have a machine that can handle cloth diapers. With three little ones, I will not have time to babysit this machine and scoop out suds. My wish list is still the same so the search continues. If you need a machine to do some heavy duty cleaning, keep looking. This machine can only handle ligth weight laundry and even then I'm not sure I would recommend it.

text: Installed easily and worked like a champ. I have intermediate handyman skills, nothing advanced. But I was able to figure out what was wrong and figured it was worth a try. I thought it might be the gas valve at first because the old igniter was glowing red hot. But I read further and learned that igniters start getting weak over time. Mine was about 10 years old. If it is too weak it won't open the gas valve. That is a pretty smart design if you ask me. You only want gas to go into the oven if it is going to ignite and that is what the igniter/gas valve work together to do. The clue that my old igniter was bad was that I didn't smell gas when I turned the oven on even though the igniter was glowing red (but it wasn't glowing hot enough anymore). So, it cost me some time to figure all that out but I saved some money because I did it myself.
